The limit of detection (LOD) is estimated from 3σ/S, where σ is the standard deviation of blank measurements and S is the slope of calibration curve. The LOD values of 3 are 5.90 nM in methanol that is very low LOD compared to other luminescent probes [17,41–50], as well as 0.17 μM in water that is lower than the infectious dosage of bacterial endospores (60 μM) to humans (Table 1
                        ). In aqueous media, compound 3 can enhance the sensitivity over a broad range of detections from 20−100 μM of DPA (Table 1). Moreover, the luminescent color change of 3 upon DPA addition can be obviously observed (red-orange → orange-yellow) in methanol and (red-orange → green) in aqueous solution (Fig. 2
                        ). Comparing the single emission sensor’s performance for DPA sensing [17,44,45], compound 3 based on self-calibrating detection also shows low LOD value, wide linearity, discriminative color change and various phase for detection. Using ratiometric detection instead of single emission, the fluctuation and error of the intensity-based measurement of single emission can be eliminated. Therefore, it not only reveals the merit of higher reliability with the self-calibration, but can also detect DPA in a wide range of both nM and μM of concentrations which are at a normal human level and at a risk level for infection (Table 1).

The sensing mechanism of compound 3 in both methanol and water may be explained by the energy transfer from DPA to Tb3+ and Eu3+ centers. In methanol solution, without DPA addition, the energy transfer from Tb3+ ion to Eu3+ ion is effective producing red-orange emission of compound 3. In the presence of 800 nM DPA, the luminescent color was changed from red-orange to orange-yellow which was confirmed by electrospray ionization mass spectrometry (ESI-MS) and DFT calculation. ESI-MS spectra confirmed the partial dissociation of 3 to form complexes between both lanthanoid ions and DPA (Figs. 4
                         and S18). Upon DPA addition to 3, the mass spectra showed weak peak at m/z 320.25, 313.19, 331.20 and 345.22 corresponding to the following complexes: [Tb(DPA)]+, [Eu(DPA)]+, [Eu2(1,4-phda)(DPA)]2+ and [Tb2(1,4-phda)(DPA)(H2O)]2+ (Figs. 4 and S18). Based on DFT calculation, the lowest triplet energy level of DPA (25,510 cm−1) and 1,4-phda (23,301 cm−1) (Fig. 5
                        ) can allow energy transfer to both lanthanoid ions. However, the luminescent intensity of Tb3+ is dominant compared with that of Eu3+ which is attributed to more suitable energy level of the triplet state of DPA (25,510 cm−1) and 1,4-phda (23,301 cm−1) for Tb3+ ion (20,500 cm−1) than Eu3+ (17,200 cm−1) leading to dominant enhancement of Tb3+ and slightly increased luminescent intensity of Eu3+. In water, the sensing mechanism can be described in the same manner as methanol solution. However, the luminescent color is gradually changed upon DPA addition of 100 μM becoming green emission that can be ascribed as an increased degree of complexation between DPA and Tb(III). This offers high degree of energy transfer from DPA to well matched Tb3+ ion, leading to green color emission. As a result, the luminescent color switched from red-orange to green in water.
